comments.author: BitMaxz
comments.body: Debug.log is a record of all bitcoin core operations and errors.So what exactly do you want to achieve?Do you just want to check if the address you found from debug.log have funds?Then use block explorer like blockchair.com and check if the address has a balance.Take note the address that you found is just a public key without a private key you can't able to send BTC to another BTC address.

comments.author: DaveF
comments.body: Where did you get the wallet.dat file?How long have you had it?How old is the wallet.dat file? If it's VERY old newer versions of core may not be able to open it. You would have to download older versions of it and let them update the file.DO A LOT OF BACKUPS BEFORE DOING ANYTING.Also, are you sure it's a wallet.dat from bitcoin and not an altcoin? 1000s of different alts all forked from BTC all use the same name wallet.datAnd again.DO BACKUPS.-Dave

comments.author: DaveF
comments.body: You can find some older version here:https://bitcoin.org/bin/insecure/bitcoin-core-0.8.6/https://bitcoin.org/bin/insecure/bitcoin-core-0.9.5/https://bitcoin.org/bin/bitcoin-core-0.10.3/ If you need older then 0.8.6 you will have to hunt for it a bit.The older versions will not sync with the blockchain but once you open your wallet you can get the privkeys and import them into a newer version. You can also use tools like pywallet: https://github.com/jackjack-jj/pywallet   https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=34028.0   to get your private keys out and import them into something newer.-Dave
